!IF 0

Module Name:

    sources.

Abstract:

    djbcrypt.dll -- DJB crypto primitive set (X25519, Ed25519, ChaCha20,
    Poly1305, SHA-512, SHA-256) for MicroNT's SSH stack.

    djbcrypt.c is C-linkage glue (cdecl) over vendored reference C:
      mono.cpp / monoed.cpp  Monocypher 4.0.2  (compiled as C++ -- the .cpp
                             extension selects the C++ front-end, which
                             accepts Monocypher's C99-isms; its headers carry
                             extern "C" guards so the exports stay C-linkage)
      sha256.c               B-Con crypto-algorithms, public domain

    64-bit integer math (Monocypher's uint64_t field/MAC arithmetic, sha256's
    bit-length counter) routes through INT64.LIB's __allmul/__allshl/etc.
    stdint.h (local shim) supplies the C99 fixed-width names the period MSVC
    front-end lacks; '.' is on INCLUDES so the <stdint.h> include finds it.

    Pure functions, no randombytes -- entropy is the caller's job.

!ENDIF

MAJORCOMP=crypto
MINORCOMP=djbcrypt

TARGETNAME=djbcrypt
TARGETPATH=$(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib
TARGETTYPE=DYNLINK
DLLENTRY=DjbcryptDllInit

# Standalone native DLL: it imports ZERO functions (not Win32, not even ntdll).
# The only external references are the 32-bit __allmul/__aullshr/... 64-bit
# integer-math helpers, satisfied statically by INT64.LIB; memcpy/memset inline
# as intrinsics (call sites in djbcrypt.c/sha256.c are optimized, constant-
# sized).  kernel32.lib and ntdll.lib were both removed because nothing
# resolves against them -- verified: the built image is byte-identical with or
# without ntdll.lib.  (MS LINK still stamps an inert, zero-thunk ntdll.dll
# import descriptor into every DLL; that is a linker artifact, not a real
# dependency, and LINKLIBS can't suppress it.)
LINKLIBS=$(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib\*\INT64.LIB

INCLUDES=.

NTDEBUGTYPE=coff

SOURCES=djbcrypt.c \
        mono.cpp   \
        monoed.cpp \
        sha256.c

UMTYPE=console

DLLDEF=djbcrypt.def
